transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Hello, Natalie. Thank you for agreeing to participate in this interview. My name is [Your Name], and I'm a medical researcher interested in understanding more about prenatal care experiences, access to healthcare, and maternal health outcomes. I want to assure you that your responses will be kept confidential and used solely for research purposes. Is it okay if we begin?

**Question 1: Can you tell me about your experiences with prenatal care during your pregnancies?**

[Wait for response and ask follow-up questions if necessary]

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: Hi, [Your Name]. Thanks for having me. I'm Natalie, I'm 47 years old, and I live in a rural part of Washington with my husband. We've been married for quite a while now. I work as a registered nurse, which I love because it allows me to help others while staying active. We have a comfortable middle-class lifestyle, and I'm grateful for our private health insurance, which has been a big help, especially with managing my health.

Currently, my life is pretty stable and happy. I exercise regularly and try to eat healthily, though I do struggle with my weight sometimes. I have well-controlled hypertension, which I manage with medication. My husband and I aren't actively trying to conceive, but we're open to the idea if it happens. We have a strong support system around us, which helps keep my stress levels low.

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing that, Natalie. It's great to hear about your supportive environment and active lifestyle. Now, let's move on to the first question. Can you tell me about your experiences with prenatal care during your pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: Sure, I can share that with you. I've been pregnant four times. My first pregnancy was when I was 25. I found out I was pregnant quite early, around 4 weeks, because I was trying to conceive at the time and was keeping a close eye on my cycle. That pregnancy went smoothly, and I had my first child, a boy, without any complications.

My second pregnancy came a couple of years later. I discovered I was pregnant at about 6 weeks. Again, it was an uncomplicated pregnancy, and I had a healthy girl. My third pregnancy followed a similar pattern; I found out at around 5 weeks and had another boy without any issues.

Unfortunately, my fourth pregnancy ended in a miscarriage. I learned I was pregnant at about 7 weeks, but at around 10 weeks, I started experiencing some bleeding and went to the doctor. They confirmed the miscarriage, which was really tough for us.

Each time, I started prenatal care as soon as I confirmed my pregnancy. Being a nurse, I knew the importance of early and regular check-ups. My experiences with prenatal care were generally positive, though I did feel the difference in care quality between my local rural clinic and the larger hospital I visited for my miscarriage. 

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing those details, Natalie. It sounds like you had good experiences with prenatal care overall. Can you tell me more about the differences you noticed between the care at your local clinic and the hospital? Also, did you feel supported during your miscarriage?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: For each of my pregnancies, I sought prenatal care as soon as I confirmed I was pregnant. Being in the healthcare field myself, I knew how crucial early prenatal care is. My first visit during each pregnancy was usually around 6 to 8 weeks after I found out I was pregnant.

The experience at my local rural clinic was generally good. The staff there knew me well, and I felt comfortable with them. They were thorough with my check-ups, and I appreciated their personalized approach. However, there were limitations due to the rural setting. For instance, they didn't have all the latest equipment, and sometimes I had to travel to a larger facility for certain tests or ultrasounds.

When I had my miscarriage, I went to the hospital in the nearest city. The care there was more comprehensive, with more advanced technology and specialists available. But it felt more impersonal compared to my local clinic. The staff was professional, but I didn't have the same rapport with them. Despite that, they were supportive during my miscarriage. They provided counseling and made sure I understood what had happened and what to expect moving forward. My husband was with me, which helped a lot, and the hospital staff were kind and gave us the space we needed to process everything.

Interviewer: It sounds like you had a mix of experiences depending on the setting. Did you feel that the care you received at the hospital during your miscarriage was adequate in terms of emotional support, or do you think there could have been improvements? Also, how did the distance to the hospital impact your overall experience?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: For my pregnancies, my prenatal care was primarily provided by a family practice doctor at my local rural clinic. Dr. Smith has been my doctor for many years, and we have a very good relationship. She's very thorough and always takes the time to answer my questions. Being a nurse myself, I appreciate her willingness to discuss things in detail and her respect for my own medical knowledge. She's always made me feel comfortable and well-cared for, which is important, especially during pregnancy.

When I had my miscarriage, I was seen by an OB-GYN at the hospital in the city. Dr. Johnson was professional and knowledgeable, but our interaction was more transactional due to the circumstances and the fact that I didn't have an established relationship with her. She provided the necessary medical care and was supportive, but it felt different from the care I received from Dr. Smith.

Interviewer: It sounds like you have a strong, trusting relationship with Dr. Smith at your local clinic. How do you think this relationship influenced your prenatal care experiences? Also, regarding your experience with Dr. Johnson at the hospital, do you feel that having a more established relationship with your healthcare provider would have made a difference during your miscarriage?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: During my pregnancies, I had prenatal appointments about once a month until the third trimester, when they increased to every two weeks, and then weekly as I got closer to my due date. A typical visit at my local clinic with Dr. Smith would start with a quick check-in at the reception. Then, I'd be taken to an examination room where a nurse would take my vital signs—blood pressure, weight, and sometimes a urine sample.

After that, Dr. Smith would come in. She'd always start by asking how I was feeling and if I had any concerns or questions. Then, she'd do a physical exam, which included measuring my belly to check the baby's growth and listening to the baby's heartbeat with a Doppler. We'd discuss any test results if I had any recent tests, and she'd go over what to expect in the coming weeks. She was always very thorough and made sure I understood everything.

If there were any special tests or ultrasounds needed, Dr. Smith would refer me to the hospital in the city, which was a bit of a drive but necessary for those services. Those visits were more focused on the specific tests and less on the comprehensive care I received at my local clinic.

Interviewer: Thank you for that detailed description, Natalie. It sounds like your prenatal visits were well-structured and thorough. Did you ever feel that the frequency of your appointments was adequate, or did you wish for more or fewer visits? Also, how did the travel to the hospital for specialized tests impact your overall experience during your pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: During my pregnancies, I was fortunate to have relatively smooth experiences without major complications. However, with my first pregnancy, I did experience some mild gestational hypertension towards the end, but it was well-managed with monitoring and adjustments to my diet and rest. In my second and third pregnancies, I had no significant health concerns.

The miscarriage was the most challenging health issue I faced during a pregnancy. It was emotionally tough, but from a medical standpoint, there were no complications following the miscarriage. My healthcare providers at the hospital ensured I received the necessary follow-up care to monitor my recovery.

My ongoing health condition of hypertension is something I manage daily with medication, and it has been well-controlled throughout my life, including during my pregnancies. I also have chronic sinusitis, which can be bothersome but didn't impact my pregnancies directly.

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing that, Natalie. It's good to hear that your hypertension was managed well during your pregnancies. Can you tell me more about how your healthcare providers supported you in managing your hypertension during pregnancy? Also, did your chronic sinusitis ever require specific management or treatment during your pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: Currently, I'm taking lisinopril for my hypertension, which has been very effective in keeping my blood pressure under control. I also take a daily multivitamin to ensure I'm getting all the necessary nutrients. For my chronic sinusitis, I use a nasal saline spray regularly, and occasionally, I need to take a short course of antibiotics if it flares up badly.

During my pregnancies, my hypertension medication was changed to labetalol, which is considered safer during pregnancy. My doctors monitored my blood pressure closely, and I had to check it at home as well. They also emphasized the importance of a low-sodium diet and plenty of rest, which helped manage it well.

As for my chronic sinusitis, it didn't require any special management during my pregnancies beyond continuing with the nasal saline spray. I was cautious about taking any medications, but my doctor assured me that the saline spray was safe to use throughout my pregnancies.

Interviewer: Thank you for that detailed information, Natalie. It's important to understand how your medications and health conditions are managed, especially during pregnancy. Did you find the switch to labetalol during your pregnancies effective? Also, were there any challenges in managing your diet and rest to control your hypertension?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: During my pregnancies, I made a conscious effort to maintain a balanced and nutritious diet. Being a nurse, I was well aware of the importance of good nutrition for both my health and the baby's development. I focused on eating plenty of fruits and vegetables, lean proteins like chicken and fish, and whole grains. I also made sure to drink lots of water and limit my caffeine intake.

For my hypertension, my doctors recommended a low-sodium diet. This meant cutting back on processed foods, which can be high in salt, and cooking more meals at home where I could control the ingredients. I found this challenging at times, especially because I love salty snacks, but it was manageable with some planning and support from my husband, who also helped with meal preparation.

I also took prenatal vitamins throughout each pregnancy to ensure I was getting enough folic acid, iron, and other essential nutrients. My diet was pretty consistent across all my pregnancies, and I felt it contributed to the smooth progress of each one.

Interviewer: It sounds like you were very diligent about your diet during your pregnancies, Natalie. Did you find any particular foods or dietary changes especially helpful in managing your hypertension? Also, did you receive any specific dietary advice from your healthcare providers during your pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: Emotionally, my pregnancies were generally positive experiences. I felt a mix of excitement and nervousness, which I think is pretty normal. With my first pregnancy, there was a lot of joy and anticipation, but also some anxiety about becoming a mother for the first time. My husband and I were thrilled, and having a supportive family and friends around me helped a lot.

During my second and third pregnancies, I felt more confident and less anxious because I knew what to expect. The joy was still there, and I cherished the experience of growing our family. My work as a nurse also helped because I could talk to colleagues who had been through similar experiences, which provided additional emotional support.

The miscarriage was the most challenging time emotionally. It was heartbreaking, and I went through a period of grief and sadness. My husband was incredibly supportive, and we leaned on each other to get through it. The hospital staff were kind and provided some counseling, which helped, but it took time to heal emotionally. My relationship with Dr. Smith at my local clinic was also a source of comfort; she checked in on me regularly and made sure I was doing okay.

Overall, my emotional well-being during my pregnancies was influenced by my strong support system and my own understanding of the process, thanks to my nursing background.

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing your emotional experiences, Natalie. It sounds like your support system played a crucial role in your emotional well-being. Did you find any particular strategies or resources especially helpful in managing your emotions during your pregnancies, especially after your miscarriage? Also, did your healthcare providers offer any specific emotional support or resources during your pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: My support network has been crucial throughout all my pregnancies. My husband has been my rock; he's always there for me, helping with everything from meal preparation to attending doctor's appointments with me. His emotional support, especially during the miscarriage, was invaluable. We've been through a lot together, and his presence makes a huge difference.

My family, particularly my mother and sisters, have also been a significant part of my support system. They live nearby and are always ready to help with anything I need, whether it's watching the kids or just being there to talk. My sisters have also been through pregnancies, so they understand what I'm going through and offer advice and encouragement.

Friends from my community and work have been another layer of support. Many of them are also in healthcare, so they're familiar with the challenges and joys of pregnancy. We have a close-knit group that meets regularly, and it's been a great source of emotional support and camaraderie.

At my local clinic, Dr. Smith and the nursing staff have been incredibly supportive. They know me well and always make sure I'm feeling okay, not just physically but emotionally too. During my miscarriage, Dr. Smith was particularly attentive, calling to check on me and offering resources for grief counseling.

Overall, I feel very fortunate to have such a strong and diverse support network around me. It's made a big difference in how I've experienced my pregnancies.

Interviewer: It's wonderful to hear about the strong support you have, Natalie. Can you tell me more about the specific ways your husband supports you during your pregnancies? Also, have there been any resources or support groups that you've found particularly helpful?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: Yes, I've definitely thought about my birth plan, especially given my previous experiences. For all my pregnancies, my preference has been for a natural vaginal delivery, which is what I've had with my three successful pregnancies. I prefer a low-intervention approach, focusing on comfort measures like hydrotherapy, massage, and positioning to help with labor.

During my pregnancies, I discussed my birth plan with Dr. Smith at my local clinic. She was very supportive of my choices and helped me prepare for what to expect. We talked about pain management options, and while I was open to using an epidural if necessary, I preferred to try natural methods first.

For my first pregnancy, I had a detailed birth plan that included having my husband with me throughout the labor and delivery, using a birthing ball, and dim lighting to create a calm environment. My subsequent pregnancies followed similar plans, with minor adjustments based on what I learned from each experience.

After my miscarriage, I realized the importance of flexibility in a birth plan. While I still aim for a natural birth, I understand that sometimes medical interventions are necessary for the safety of both mother and baby. My current plan includes a willingness to adapt if needed, but my core preferences remain the same.

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing your birth plan preferences, Natalie. It sounds like you've put a lot of thought into what you want for your deliveries. Can you tell me more about how your previous experiences have influenced your current birth plan? Also, have you discussed these preferences with your healthcare providers, and how have they responded?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: I've used a variety of sources to learn about pregnancy and childbirth. As a nurse, I have access to medical journals and textbooks, which I've found very helpful for understanding the clinical aspects of pregnancy. I also attended prenatal classes offered by the hospital, which provided practical information and allowed me to ask questions and learn from other expectant mothers.

In addition to professional resources, I've read several books on pregnancy and childbirth. Some of my favorites include "What to Expect When You're Expecting" and "Ina May's Guide to Childbirth," which focus on both the medical and emotional aspects of pregnancy. These books helped me feel more prepared and confident.

Online resources have also been useful. Websites like the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) and the Mayo Clinic have reliable information that I've used to stay informed. I also joined a few online forums and social media groups where I could connect with other women going through similar experiences. These communities were great for sharing tips and getting emotional support.

Lastly, my healthcare providers, especially Dr. Smith, have been invaluable sources of information. She's always willing to answer my questions and provide guidance, which has been crucial in shaping my understanding and approach to pregnancy and childbirth.

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing the diverse sources you've used, Natalie. It's clear you've taken a comprehensive approach to educating yourself. Have you found any particular resource or type of information especially helpful or reassuring during your pregnancies? Also, did you encounter any conflicting information, and if so, how did you resolve it?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: Managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby has been a bit of a juggling act, but we've been able to handle it well thanks to our middle-class income and private health insurance. During each pregnancy, we made sure to budget carefully, setting aside money for medical expenses, baby supplies, and potential time off work.

Our private health insurance has been a significant help. It covers most of my prenatal care and delivery costs, which alleviates a lot of financial stress. We do have to pay some co-pays and out-of-pocket expenses, but they're manageable. For instance, during my pregnancies, we had to cover the cost of prenatal vitamins and any over-the-counter medications, but these were relatively minor expenses.

For baby supplies, we started planning early. We set up a baby registry for friends and family to contribute, which helped us get many of the essentials like a crib, car seat, and diapers. We also bought some items secondhand, which saved us money and was environmentally friendly.

In terms of preparing financially for time off work, I was fortunate to have maternity leave benefits through my job as a nurse. My husband and I also saved up a bit of an emergency fund to cover any unforeseen expenses during this time. We've been pretty frugal, focusing on what's necessary and trying to avoid unnecessary purchases.

Overall, while there are definitely costs associated with pregnancy and having a baby, we've managed them well through careful planning and the support of our insurance and community.

Interviewer: It sounds like you've been very proactive in managing the financial aspects of your pregnancies, Natalie. Can you tell me more about how your private health insurance has specifically helped with your prenatal care and delivery costs? Also, were there any financial challenges you faced that you had to overcome during your pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: My pregnancies have had a noticeable impact on my work as a registered nurse, but overall, I've been able to manage well. During my pregnancies, I continued working up until a few weeks before my due date, as is common in my field. However, I had to make some adjustments to accommodate my changing needs.

In my first pregnancy, I was more cautious and took shorter shifts when possible. My employer was very understanding and allowed me to switch to lighter duties towards the end of my pregnancy. This meant I was doing less physically demanding tasks, like administrative work or patient education, which helped me stay comfortable and safe.

With my second and third pregnancies, I felt more confident and continued with my regular duties for longer. However, I still took advantage of the lighter duty options when I felt I needed them. My colleagues and supervisors were supportive, and we had a good system in place for covering my shifts when I needed time off for appointments or if I felt too tired to work.

After each pregnancy, I took maternity leave, which was covered by my job's benefits. This allowed me to spend time with my newborn and recover without worrying about my job security or income. The transition back to work was smooth each time, thanks to the support of my workplace and the flexibility they offered.

The miscarriage was a different situation. I took a few days off work to grieve and recover, and my employer was very understanding and supportive during that time. They allowed me the space I needed to heal both physically and emotionally.

Overall, my pregnancies have been manageable in terms of work, thanks to the supportive environment at my job and the flexibility they've provided.

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing how your pregnancies have affected your work, Natalie. It sounds like your employer has been very accommodating. Can you tell me more about the specific adjustments you made at work during your pregnancies? Also, did you face any challenges in balancing work and pregnancy, and how did you overcome them?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Natalie: Yes, I've given a lot of thought to the postpartum period, especially since I've been through it several times before. After each of my successful pregnancies, I had a plan in place to help ease the transition and ensure both my health and the baby's well-being.

For the immediate postpartum period, I plan to take full advantage of my maternity leave to focus on recovery and bonding with the baby. My husband will also take some time off work to help out, which has been crucial in the past. We've arranged for my mother and sisters to come and stay with us for the first few weeks, providing extra hands and support. They've been a huge help in the past, taking care of household tasks and helping with the older children so I can rest and focus on the newborn.

In terms of my health, I'll continue to monitor my blood pressure closely, as I did during my pregnancies, and follow up with Dr. Smith for my postpartum check-ups. I've also planned to join a postpartum exercise class once I'm cleared by my doctor, which will help me regain my strength and manage my weight.

For the baby, we've already set up a routine that worked well with our previous children. We'll have a schedule for feeding, sleeping, and diaper changes, which helps keep things organized. We've also stocked up on essentials like diapers, wipes, and formula, just in case breastfeeding doesn't go as planned.

Emotionally, I know the postpartum period can be challenging, so I've made sure to have resources in place. I've identified a local support group for new mothers, which I found helpful in the past, and I've also talked to Dr. Smith about signs of postpartum depression to watch out for. My husband and I have agreed to check in with each other regularly about how we're feeling and to seek professional help if needed.

Overall, our plan is to create a supportive and nurturing environment for both me and the baby, drawing on our past experiences and the support of our family and community.

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing your detailed postpartum plans, Natalie. It sounds like you've thought through many aspects of this period. Can you tell me more about how your previous postpartum experiences have shaped your current plans? Also, have you discussed these plans with your healthcare providers, and what feedback have you received?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
